There are a lot of rookie mistakes you can make as a first time homebuyer. Here are some of the ones we see most often:
1. Underestimating the costs- 
Overestimating how much home you can afford & underestimating the real cost of home buying ( closing costs, homeowners insurance, property taxes, etc,) 
2. Going solo- 
The home buying process can get very complicated if you attempt to go about it alone. Lean on your local loan officers and realtors to alleviate some of that stress. 
3. Making big purchases before you buy-
Depending on your credit score and history, larger transactions can lower your score, which can impact the interest rate and loan amount you could receive. 
4. Skipping the home inspection-
*DON’T DO THIS*
Home inspections can help you discover any potential problems with the property that might be difficult to see on the surface like faulty wiring, foundation issues, mold, etc. 

For more info on the home buying process, contact me below ✨

Just because you’ve been pre approved doesn’t mean that you are free and clear to make big purchases before closing day.

When a lender grants you a preapproval, it’s based on the financial details you provide. With that, a preapproval is a type of conditional approval.

If your financial situation changes, the lender may change its mind about their preapproval. That’s totally within the lender’s rights. The mortgage underwriter will check your credit score as close to closing as possible to make sure your financial situation hasn’t changed. If it has, an applicant can be denied a mortgage.

Long story short: wait to buy that brand new Bugatti until after you close on your house. 

#lorivadengroup #tiptuesday #dontdothis #homebuyers #mistakes #realestate

Did you know that there are some questions that your realtor has to be very careful when answering?

✅ Questions about the house itself (SAFE!) 

❌ Questions like: is this a good place to raise a family? What kind of people live in this area? How old are my neighbors? Are there a lot of (specific religious group) around here? Etc. 

This is NOT because they are unaware of the answer or because they are trying to withhold information, It’s actually because they’re attempting to stay on the right side of the Fair Housing Act, which prohibits housing discrimination based on race, religion, sex, or family/economic status.

When you are working with a realtor, make sure that they present you with the facts and statistics instead of their options. This is the easiest way to avoid issues with the federal fair housing act & still getting all of your questions answered!!

Now you know ✨

#lorivaden  #texasrealtor #homevalue #buywithconfidence #texasrealestate

Many sellers attempt to go it alone instead of hiring an agent to save on commission costs, only to find out it’s not as easy as sticking a For Sale sign in their front yard and snapping a few photos of the home.

In reality, FSBO sellers often run the risk of losing money. This can happen in several ways, a few of which are as follows:

. FSBO sellers can price their home too high, meaning it could take months to receive an offer or too low and leave money on the table.

.  FSBO are usually not well-versed in the language of offers, counter-offers, and contracts, and we can be more susceptible to potential pitfalls.

If you’re considering selling your home FSBO, ask yourself: is it worth the stress and time? Is this really the type of task you want to DIY? At the end of the day, you’re better off hiring a professional with the skills, knowledge, and resources to set you up for success in your sale. A good REALTOR® will be worth every penny.

These have easily been the hardest and most emotional days of my life, and it’s only Wednesday 😭. Swipe for a short summary of our roller coaster of a week with baby Ava & Please keep us in your prayers 🙏💖

✨UPDATE✨

I have officially reached the “I don’t need a table, I am the table” stage of pregnancy 😂.
Enjoying what could be my last few weeks with miss Ava in my belly. 

#babyterkla #update

It’s all about the little wins! 

Our latest sonogram with the high risk doctor revealed that the mass is stable (not growing or showing any changes) so she is clearing us to stick with our original OB and hospital for delivery. Also, baby girl decided to flip over night and is now head down so no scheduled C- Section, she can just come whenever she feels ready 🥹🙌 

I am unbelievably grateful for all of your support, prayers, and positive messages since we found out about this last week! We have faith that everything is in God’s hands and whatever the mass turns out to be, we will be ready to get it treated if and when it requires treatment. 🙏

Still processing that in less than 48 hours, I will be holding the tiny human that has been cooking in my belly for the last 9 months🥹

If you have been following along with Ava’s story, you know that her scheduled C Section is going to be on Sunday morning. We have an amazing team of doctors and surgeons that will be running tests and capturing images of her abdomen during our time at the hospital and we have faith that those results will lead to a diagnosis that requires little to no invasive surgery or negative long term effects. 

I feel super grateful for the outpouring of love, prayers, and positive vibes that we have gotten since we started sharing her story and I really can’t tell you what an incredible effect they have had on us and this whole situation. From the bottom of my heart, thank y’all so much!! 

Stay tuned, the next picture I post will be of our sweet baby girl 💖
